<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIOLENCE POLARIZES EL SALVADOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I was shocked and then grimly satisfied to read the excerpt from the writing of 
the Rev. Ellacuria. Clearly, he advocates and justifies terrorism, although not 
at all creatively; the arguments he puts forth have been previously stated in 
humanistic terms by philosophers, sociologists and psychologists for 200 or 300 
years. And yet, he makes perfect sense. 
</P>
<P>
Should not those who engage in, advocate, or support oppressive violence expect 
to meet with violent punishment at the hands of those they have harmed? And 
indeed, the Rev. Ellacuria, a supporter of the oppressive violence of 
communism, which is even now being torn down by angry people all around the 
world, has met with his own punishment. With his death, justice is served. 
</P>
<P>
JIM NELSON 
</P>
<P>
Irvine 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120289-0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 142672 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 2, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 3; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
199 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIOLENCE POLARIZES EL SALVADOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In reading the excerpts from "Freedom Made Flesh," by Rev. Ignacio Ellacuria 
(Op-Ed Page, Nov. 21), one feels compelled to ask, which is most evil in El 
Salvador, the left-leaning rebels (communists to us), the militarists running 
the country, or the Roman Catholic Church? Sadly, the answer is that all are 
equally culpable and will have the blood of the people on their hands for many 
years to come. 
</P>
<P>
The now deceased Rev. Ellacuria saw "good violence" mandated by his 
interpretation of the Bible, as something which was liberating, a kind of 
rightful wrath. Shame on all who think this way. No good reasons can be 
advanced to support murder and destruction. It is no surprise that he died at 
the hand of violence, it seems clear that he called it on himself. 
</P>
<P>
What solace may have been possible for the El Salvadorans by their church and 
its clergy has clearly disappeared. History has shown repeatedly that when 
religious institutions are actively a part of the political process or attempt 
to usurp it, substituting one hierarchical model of violent authority for 
another, democratic processes are overwhelmed and government by consensus 
becomes impossible. 
</P>
<P>
JAMES BLOCK 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
