<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIOLENCE POLARIZES EL SALVADOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a former chief of the political section of our embassy in San Salvador, I 
fully share the views of George Black and Anne Nelson on the outrageous torture 
and murder of the Jesuit priests ("Why the Right Would Slay Priests in El 
Salvador," Opinion, Nov. 26). The circumstances of the slaughter and subsequent 
developments make it a safe bet that the national record of never trying a 
military officer for human rights violations will remain unblemished. 
</P>
<P>
Let us not forget that, in the brief period between Ronald Reagan's election 
and inauguration, the Salvadoran hard-liners celebrated the political demise of 
Jimmy Carter and his human rights policy by assassinating six leaders of the 
legal opposition, four American religious women and two American land reform 
advisers. Now they are sending another clear message of their determination 
never to share power -- least of all to let themselves be ousted like the 
Somozas of Nicaragua. 
</P>
<P>
In a country that has become increasingly polarized in violence since the 
wholesale massacres of 1932, the issue is not whether President Alfredo 
Cristiani was democratically elected. It is whether he or any other civilian 
leader can avert or punish such acts of terrorism while seriously negotiating 
with the rebel forces. 
</P>
<P>
MARSHALL PHILLIPS 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
