<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE'S DRINKING WATER SUPPLY FROM DELTA FACES NEW THREAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Southern California we cannot survive on water supplies available locally; 
natural supplies meet less than one-third of our current needs. We must import 
the rest from Northern California and from the Colorado River. Now, according 
to your editorial, another element, a suspected cancer-causing agent, 
trihalomethane, has been added to the controversy surrounding Southern 
California's need for water from the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta. 
</P>
<P>
Water demands in Southern California are expected to increase roughly 20% by 
the year 2000. Our region still faces a highly undependable water supply in the 
future even though we lead the state in efficient use of water, including water 
conservation, water reclamation and ground-water management. Without a 
reliable, high-quality water supply, Southern California cannot avoid the 
adverse impact on our economy, our life styles, our very livelihood. 
</P>
<P>
The latest report of potential contamination of one of Southern California's 
important sources of water adds urgency to the cry that elected officials and 
policy-makers address the management and optimum utilization of this most 
precious resource. In providing us with the keys to the solutions, these 
decision-makers can place emphasis on understanding and appreciating the water 
needs of all regions and all sectors of the state, and build a bridge of 
cooperation among them all. 
</P>
<P>
A solution is out there. Everyone needs to be involved. 
</P>
<P>
JOAN WILSON ANDERSON 
</P>
<P>
Executive Director 
</P>
<P>
Southern California Water Committee Inc. 
</P>
<P>
Irvine 
</P>
</TEXT>
