<LENGTH>
<P>
318 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP MUSIC REVIEW: IGLESIAS SHEDS CASANOVA IMAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Julio Iglesias has a popular image as a sort of Latin George Hamilton, thanks 
in part to pop hits of a few years ago such as the regrettable "To All the 
Girls I've Loved Before," which is no longer part of his concert repertoire. To 
see him live these days is to see something different altogether: In the best 
moments of his show Thursday at the Pantages, Iglesias came off more in the 
Sinatra mold circa "Only the Lonely," more Mr. Solitude than Mr. Casanova, a 
quiet, intensely serious figure of studied isolation. Which only makes women 
love him more, of course. 
</P>
<P>
For an international romantic idol, his moves aren't all that smooth; they're 
so subtle you almost need a motion detector to pick them out. As he sings of 
broken love in relatively unbroken English as well as French and his native 
Spanish, his hand balls into a fist, then arches, and his arm goes out to his 
side, barely controlled, like Joe Cocker cast as a suave, jilted gigolo in 
black tie. The lyrics may have been unintelligible to English-only attendees, 
but the body language said: "Ouch." 
</P>
<P>
If his performing style is nicely understated these days, so is his backing 
band, which provides plenty of subtle Latin rhythms, dominated by synthesizer 
washes. This is in sharp contrast to the unsubtle Disco Julio of a few years 
back, whose unfortunate attempts at self-Americanization sold millions of 
records to new Anglo fans but turned off a lot of old Latin ones. Happily, 
there were few signs that this stop on his international tour was specifically 
tailored for the American audience he once seemed desperate to court. 
</P>
<P>
"Thank you for paying so much money tonight for the kids," Iglesias told the 
ethnically diverse, sold-out house, referring not to baby-sitters, but to the 
fact that half the proceeds from the show were earmarked to go through UNICEF 
to primary health care projects throughout Latin America. CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120289-0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 142872 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 2, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
<P>
Correction Appended 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 8; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
925 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP BEAT: REACTIONS MIXED OVER MCCARTNEY'S TALK OF BEATLES REUNION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paul, George and Ringo together again? 
</P>
<P>
Paul says he'd love to. 
</P>
<P>
George says no thank you. 
</P>
<P>
Ringo says no comment. 
</P>
<P>
If the three surviving members of rock's most celebrated group disagree over a 
possible reunion project, fans too seemed to have mixed feelings. 
</P>
<P>
The prospect of some kind of Beatles reunion has come up frequently since the 
group dissolved two decades ago, but all four principals always rejected it. 
John Lennon's death in 1980 brought renewed calls for the surviving three to 
get together, but various legal and personal differences have kept them apart. 
</P>
<P>
But with the lawsuits all settled recently, McCartney said at a Monday press 
conference in Los Angeles that he would be interested in finally teaming up 
again with his ex-mates. And once again, the fans are intrigued. The general 
feeling: a mix of nostalgic elation, but doubts about whether the "magic" would 
still be there and whether it would be proper to proceed without Lennon. 
</P>
<P>
At Pepperland Records in Anaheim, a store that highlights Beatles music and 
memorabilia, the potential re-teaming has been a hot topic all week. 
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of talk," said store owner Mike Lefebvre. "In the concerts, Paul 
is coming across very warm and that makes a lot of customers come in here 
thinking he's a loving guy and would be happy to have the others on stage with 
him." 
</P>
<P>
Many of Pepperland's patrons were caught up in rumors that a reunion would take 
place at Wednesday's closing night of McCartney's five-concert engagement at 
the Forum. (It didn't, although both Ringo Starr and George Harrison were in 
town.) 
</P>
<P>
But Lefebvre and other Beatles enthusiasts seem torn about the prospect, 
generally agreeing with Harrison's terse response to McCartney's comments: "As 
far as I'm concerned," Harrison said in a statement Tuesday, "there will be no 
Beatles reunion so long as John Lennon remains dead." 
</P>
<P>
Said Lefebvre: "My opinion is they fear that if they got back together there 
wouldn't be the magic any more. They're probably right. They would put out good 
music, but not as good. We all have a, well, morbid curiosity, but there's a 
part of me that says, 'Why bother?' " 
</P>
<P>
Among fans surveyed in the Forum parking lot before and after Monday's 
McCartney concert, Mary Zekin's reaction was typical. The 14-year-old, who had 
come to Los Angeles from San Diego with her 19-year-old sister to see 
McCartney's concert at the Forum, was visibly elated, her eyes growing big in 
anticipation. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be the best thing in the world," she said in a burst of 
excitement. 
</P>
<P>
Her sister, Laura, concurred, stating that though Paul, George and Ringo 
couldn't be expected to recreate the old Beatles magic, "It would be a new kind 
of magic." 
</P>
<P>
But then, the initial adrenaline rush over, the Zekins nodded in agreement as 
George Emmel, a first-generation Beatles fan at 40, spoke with the dampening 
voice of reason. 
</P>
<P>
"There would always be something missing," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"We were anticipating something like that (comment by McCartney)," said Lonnie 
Pena, 31, who had traveled with two friends from Houston to see the show. "But 
there's no Lennon, so I'm not going to have high expectations." 
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, it became clear that even if Beatles fans aren't looking for a 
true reunion, they want something. 
</P>
<P>
"It would never be the Beatles again, even if John was alive," said Allen 
Weiner, a Potomac, Md.-based writer and author of the 1986 book, "The Beatles: 
A Recording History." 
</P>
<P>
But Weiner has some ideas for a second-best situation. 
</P>
<P>
"My first choice would be to get them back in the studio to do new things," 
Weiner said. "Paul and George writing together would be a neat idea. It would 
be a pressure-free situation, hopefully." 
</P>
<P>
A different fantasy is held by Pepperland's Mike Lefebvre. 
</P>
<P>
"I wouldn't like to see any songwriting type of thing," Lefebvre said. "I'd 
like to see them get together with other musicians like at some benefit and not 
just be the three of them. If they did get together, I wouldn't want it to be a 
Monkees-type reunion." 
</P>
<P>
That attitude suits some in the Beatles camp just fine. Elliot Mintz, longtime 
confidant of Lennon and Yoko Ono's spokesman, suggested that McCartney's 
announcement may have been made to draw attention to the press conference, 
which was called to announce a tour sponsorship deal with Visa. 
</P>
<P>
"If Ringo or George elected to take him up on the invitation, that's 
wonderful," said Mintz, producer and host of the ongoing "Lost Lennon Tapes" 
radio series, heard here Wednesdays at 11 p.m. on KLSX-FM. "But to me the whole 
thing seemed a little hollow. I think perhaps the invitation was extended a 
little too late." 
</P>
<P>
Speaking as a fan, Mintz was dubious about the aesthetic prospects of any kind 
of reunion. "The Beatles represented more than a musical group," he said. "They 
represent a time in history, a time in our development as a culture and a 
generation. It seems unlikely that those experiences and sensibilities can ever 
be reclaimed, and I think that any effort to do so might somehow rob us of the 
experience we once shared and revere." 
</P>
<P>
LIVE ACTION: Stevie Wonder will top a benefit concert to help educate 
inner-city youth at the Forum on Jan. 6. Tickets on sale now. . . . On sale 
today is Erasure at the Forum, Mar. 11. . . . Terence Trent D'Arby will be in 
concert at the Park Plaza Hotel on Dec. 15. Tickets on sale Monday. . . . Also 
on sale Monday is Todd Rundgren at the Wiltern Theatre, Jan. 7. . . . The 
Universal Amphitheatre has added a third Patti LaBelle show, midnight on Dec. 
22. On sale Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
