<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
NICARAGUA; 
</P>
<P>
VISAS REFUSED U.S. ELECTION OBSERVERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Sandinista government refused to allow a four-member U.S. congressional 
delegation to observe national election campaign activities because of 
Washington's financial aid to an opposition candidate. Foreign Minister Miguel 
D'Escoto said the Nicaragua has invited observers from the United Nations, the 
Organization of American States and other international agencies, including 
former President Jimmy Carter, to witness activities leading up to the Feb. 25 
elections. Congress and the Bush Administration have approved $9 million in 
contributions to opposition candidate Violeta Chamorro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
VISAS; NICARAGUA -- ELECTIONS; UNITED STATES -- FOREIGN AID -- NICARAGUA; 
UNITED STATES -- FOREIGN RELATIONS -- NICARAGUA; ELECTION FRAUD; POLITICAL 
CONTRIBUTIONS; CHAMORRO, VIOLETA BARRIOS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
