Part A; Page 16; Column 1; Foreign Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
69 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
MIDDLE EAST; 
</P>
<P>
2 YEMENS TAKE FIRST STEP TO UNIFICATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leaders of pro-Western Yemen and Marxist South Yemen signed a draft 
constitution as a first step toward the unification of the two countries on the 
tip of the Arabian Peninsula. After 18 years of intermittent talks, the two 
countries published a draft constitution and said it will be referred to their 
legislative bodies for endorsement. The two Yemens will merge into a republic 
of about 11 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
